Difference between gradients and derivatives

The gradient is a vector; it points in the direction of steepest ascent.

The directional derivative is a number; it is the rate of change when your point in ‚Ñù3
moves in that direction. 

Be careful that directional derivative of a function is a scalar while gradient is a vector.

The only difference between derivative and directional derivative is the definition of those terms. Remember:

    Directional derivative is the instantaneous rate of change (which is a scalar) of ùëì(ùë•,ùë¶)
     in the direction of the unit vector ùë¢

   Derivative is the rate of change of ùëì(ùë•,ùë¶)
   , which can be thought of the slope of the function at a point (ùë•0,ùë¶0).
   
   
